{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13001"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13001"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.46,0.41,0,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40724"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5438"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25410"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1446"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38747"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40724"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a three hour history of sudden onset of severe pain in his right leg. He has had no recent trauma but reports that over the last few months he has noticed increasing discomfort in his right leg when out walking. His medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes and he was a heavy smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 160/90 mmHg, pulse 110/min and respiratory rate 18/min. His right leg is pale, cool to touch and he cannot move his toes. His femoral pulse is weak, and the popliteal, dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial pulses cannot be felt. Sensation of the foot is notably reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations show elevated creatinine kinase levels and doppler ultrasound confirms arterial occlusion in the right Common Femoral artery\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate administration of alteplase","Emergency surgical intervention","Administration of heparin","Gradual re-warming with heating pads","Intravenous administration of nitroglycerin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is exhibiting the classic signs and symptoms of acute limb ischaemia due to an acute arterial occlusion. This is a surgical emergency that requires prompt intervention to prevent irreversible tissue damage. Acute limb ischaemia is defined as a sudden decrease in limb perfusion that can occur due to arterial embolism, arterial thrombosis, or trauma. The clinical presentation varies depending on the degree and location of the obstruction, but common findings include severe pain, pallor, pulselessness, paraesthesia, and motor weakness. In this case the laboratory investigations show elevated creatinine kinase levels, indicative of muscle ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst this patient will require some form of active intervention to overcome the obstruction, the first step in his management must be to administer \u003Cstrong\u003Eheparin\u003C/strong\u003E. Heparin is given to reduce further clot formation. This is a crucial step of the early management of acute limb ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlteplase\u003C/strong\u003E is a thrombolytic agent that can dissolve blood clots, but its use is controversial in acute limb ischaemia and carries a high risk of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGradual re-warming with heating pads\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this setting as it can exacerbate tissue injury by increasing metabolic demand and leading to further tissue ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous administration of nitroglycerin\u003C/strong\u003E: Nitroglycerin is not the primary treatment for acute limb ischaemia. It is more commonly used in conditions involving vasospasm or angina.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Heparin is the initial treatment of choice in acute limb ischaemia to prevent further clot formation and to encourage reperfusion."],"references":["Nehler MR, Duval S, Diao L, et al. Epidemiology of acute limb ischemia in the United States. J Vasc Surg. 2014 Jul;60(1): 323-8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25410"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13001"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25410"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-11-28T19:25:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-27T10:28:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5438"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40724"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":